1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:08,437
You're listening to: Hybrid Cryptography: Why Ed25519 + ML-DSA Is the Safe Migration Path.

2
00:00:08,437 --> 00:00:15,060
Why serious post-quantum rollouts combine a classical and a post-quantum algorithm instead of switching outright.

3
00:00:15,060 --> 00:00:26,911
How hybrid signatures and KEMs work, how to combine them correctly, the pitfalls, and why QAuth signs with both Ed25519 and ML-DSA-65.

4
00:00:26,911 --> 00:00:27,968
Let's get started.

5
00:00:27,968 --> 00:00:36,766
When I designed QAuth, the most important decision wasn't which post-quantum algorithm to use — it was deciding not to trust any single algorithm at all.

6
00:00:36,766 --> 00:00:46,995
QAuth signs every token with two signatures: a classical Ed25519 and a post-quantum ML-DSA-65.

7
00:00:46,995 --> 00:00:48,317
Both must verify.

8
00:00:48,317 --> 00:00:57,884
That belt-and-suspenders design is called hybrid cryptography, and in 2026 it is the consensus path for anyone who takes the migration seriously.

9
00:00:57,884 --> 00:01:05,829
This post explains why — and how to combine two algorithms correctly, because doing it wrong quietly throws away the protection.

10
00:01:05,829 --> 00:01:08,389
Now, let's talk about The dilemma hybrids solve.

11
00:01:08,389 --> 00:01:10,396
You're caught between two risks:

12
00:01:10,396 --> 00:01:24,098
Classical crypto (RSA, ECC, Ed25519) is decades-tested against classical attacks — but Shor's algorithm breaks it once a cryptographically-relevant quantum computer exists.

13
00:01:24,098 --> 00:01:26,418
(See the migration guide for the threat model.).

14
00:01:26,418 --> 00:01:33,317
Post-quantum crypto (ML-KEM, ML-DSA) resists quantum attack — but it is young.

15
00:01:33,317 --> 00:01:36,718
ML-DSA was standardized in 2024.

16
00:01:36,718 --> 00:01:45,396
We have far less cryptanalytic confidence in lattice schemes than in elliptic curves, and history is full of "proven" schemes that later cracked..

17
00:01:45,396 --> 00:01:51,718
So you're asked to bet your security on one of two algorithms, each with a different, serious failure mode.

18
00:01:51,718 --> 00:01:54,122
The hybrid answer is: don't pick.

19
00:01:54,122 --> 00:01:57,968
Use both, such that an attacker must break both to win.

20
00:01:57,968 --> 00:02:02,115
Moving on to How a hybrid is secure if either algorithm holds.

21
00:02:02,115 --> 00:02:09,675
The defining property: a hybrid construction stays secure as long as at least one of its component algorithms is unbroken.

22
00:02:09,675 --> 00:02:11,754
The threat coverage is complete:

23
00:02:11,754 --> 00:02:19,375
Scenario, Classical (Ed25519), Post-quantum (ML-DSA), Hybrid result.

24
00:02:19,375 --> 00:02:23,834
Today (no quantum computer), secure, secure, secure.

25
00:02:23,834 --> 00:02:29,038
Quantum computer arrives, broken, secure, secure (PQC holds).

26
00:02:29,038 --> 00:02:34,927
Flaw found in young lattice scheme, secure, broken, secure (classical holds).

27
00:02:34,927 --> 00:02:37,812
Both broken, broken, broken, broken.

28
00:02:37,812 --> 00:02:45,204
Only the last row defeats you — and that requires both an unforeseen lattice break and a working quantum computer.

29
00:02:45,204 --> 00:02:51,021
The hybrid converts "bet on one horse" into "an attacker must win two independent races."

30
00:02:51,021 --> 00:02:56,358
Next up: Hybrid signatures: combine by concatenation (verify both).

31
00:02:56,358 --> 00:03:07,163
For signatures, the construction is refreshingly simple and robust: sign the same message independently with each algorithm, and require both signatures to verify.

32
00:03:07,163 --> 00:03:09,795
The critical detail is the and.

33
00:03:09,795 --> 00:03:21,490
Requiring both is what gives you the "secure if either holds" guarantee for forgery: to forge a token, an attacker must forge under Ed25519 and under ML-DSA.

34
00:03:21,490 --> 00:03:23,990
This is exactly QAuth's token design.

35
00:03:23,990 --> 00:03:29,507
One subtlety worth knowing: there's a small tension between availability and security.

36
00:03:29,507 --> 00:03:34,975
Requiring both signatures maximizes unforgeability (an attacker needs both).

37
00:03:34,975 --> 00:03:39,987
If your priority were availability under a single broken scheme, you'd want the opposite.

38
00:03:39,987 --> 00:03:46,009
For authentication tokens, unforgeability is the goal — so and is correct.

39
00:03:46,009 --> 00:03:50,829
Let's explore Hybrid key exchange: combine the secrets through a KDF.

40
00:03:50,829 --> 00:03:57,043
For key exchange you can't just "verify both" — you have two shared secrets and need one session key.

41
00:03:57,043 --> 00:04:02,427
The rule: never XOR or concatenate-and-use the raw secrets directly.

42
00:04:02,427 --> 00:04:04,651
Feed both into a KDF.

43
00:04:04,651 --> 00:04:17,355
Because HKDF's output depends on all its input keying material, the session key is secure as long as either the X25519 secret or the ML-KEM secret is unknown to the attacker.

44
00:04:17,355 --> 00:04:28,605
This "KEM combiner" pattern is what TLS hybrid key exchange (X25519 + ML-KEM-768) uses in production today.

45
00:04:28,605 --> 00:04:32,055
Now let's look at Pitfalls that silently break a hybrid.

46
00:04:32,055 --> 00:04:34,387
Hybrids are easy to get subtly wrong.

47
00:04:34,387 --> 00:04:35,793
The ones I watch for:

48
00:04:35,834 --> 00:04:37,863
The "either signature passes" bug.

49
00:04:37,863 --> 00:04:47,178
Using or instead of and in verification means an attacker only has to break the weaker scheme — you've built a hybrid with the security of its worst component.

50
00:04:47,178 --> 00:04:48,115
Always and..

51
00:04:48,115 --> 00:04:49,738
Sign different messages.

52
00:04:49,738 --> 00:04:55,952
Both algorithms must sign the exact same bytes (including the same canonical encoding).

53
00:04:55,952 --> 00:05:04,125
If they sign different serializations, an attacker may mix-and-match a valid classical signature with a forged PQC one..

54
00:05:04,125 --> 00:05:06,769
Using raw KEM secrets directly.

55
00:05:06,769 --> 00:05:11,805
Skipping the KDF can leak structure or fail to bind both secrets.

56
00:05:11,805 --> 00:05:17,118
Always run both through a KEM combiner / KDF with domain separation..

57
00:05:17,118 --> 00:05:18,536
No crypto-agility.

58
00:05:18,536 --> 00:05:20,615
A hybrid is a transition tool.

59
00:05:20,615 --> 00:05:30,639
Hard-code Ed25519+ML-DSA-65 and you'll fight the same migration battle again when the next standard lands.

60
00:05:30,639 --> 00:05:34,353
Keep the algorithm names as data, per the migration guide..

61
00:05:34,353 --> 00:05:37,418
Now, let's talk about "Isn't this just twice the cost?".

62
00:05:37,418 --> 00:05:45,279
Roughly, yes — two signatures to generate and verify, two keypairs to manage, and the payload carries both.

63
00:05:45,279 --> 00:05:46,553
The honest accounting:

64
00:05:46,553 --> 00:05:48,344
Size is the real cost.

65
00:05:48,344 --> 00:06:02,118
An Ed25519 + ML-DSA-65 signature is dominated by the ~3 KB ML-DSA part; the 64-byte Ed25519 addition is negligible on top.

66
00:06:02,118 --> 00:06:06,457
(Sizes are tabulated in ML-KEM vs ML-DSA.).

67
00:06:06,457 --> 00:06:16,108
CPU is modest — Ed25519 verification is extremely fast, so adding it to ML-DSA barely moves the needle..

68
00:06:16,108 --> 00:06:30,543
For authentication and key exchange — operations measured in the thousands, not millions, per second — that overhead is a rounding error against the value of not getting your entire security stack broken by a single algorithmic surprise.

69
00:06:30,543 --> 00:06:32,106
Moving on to The takeaway.

70
00:06:32,106 --> 00:06:36,132
Hybrid cryptography is risk management expressed in code.

71
00:06:36,132 --> 00:06:49,245
You're not choosing between "trust the old crypto" and "trust the new crypto" — you're refusing to make that bet at all, and requiring an attacker to defeat both an algorithm we deeply trust and one that's quantum-resistant.

72
00:06:49,245 --> 00:06:58,512
That's why QAuth signs with Ed25519 and ML-DSA-65, and why hybrid is the safe migration path.

73
00:06:58,512 --> 00:07:12,430
Combine by and for signatures, by a KDF for key exchange, keep it agile, and you get the best of both eras of cryptography until pure PQC has earned the same trust classical crypto took decades to build.

74
00:07:12,430 --> 00:07:19,618
